Part 1: Getting started [1.5 Marks]¶

We are going to work with a credit card fraud detection dataset, consisting of transactions made by credit cards in September 2013 by European cardholders. The dataset contains only numerical input variables (V1, V2, … V28) which are the principal components obtained with PCA transformation (PCA will the introduced later in this course), due to confidentiality issues. The only features which have not been transformed with PCA are Time (seconds elapsed between each transaction and the first transaction in the dataset) and Amount (transaction Amount).\ This dataset contains 30 key features, which are not directly interpretable but contain meaningful information about the dataset. Load the dataset in CSV file using Pandas. The dataset is called creditcard.csv. Print out the first few columns of the dataset.

# Find the percentage of entries for each class
n=0
m=0
for i in df['Class']:
  if i==0:
    n+=1
  elif i==1:
    m+=1
  else:
    print(f'anomaly value {i} found')

percentage_n = (n/(n+m))*100
percentage_m = 100 - percentage_n
print(f'The percentage for first entry 1 in class is {percentage_n}%, \nThe second entry 0 in class is {percentage_m}% ')

The percentage for first entry 1 in class is 99.82725143693798%, 
The second entry 0 in class is 0.17274856306201514%

The data is considered unbalanced because over 99.82% of the total transaction are allocated to one single class 0(not fraudulent), and the remaining tiny portion is for class 1(fraudulent). Although it is normal to have this highly differnt portion in real world, the extreme bias would affect the performance of machine learning algorithm

The reason that balance/imbalance is important is that whether the data is balanced will affect the machine learning algorithm performance because the extreme bias will always result in a high testing accuracy(which is meaningless) and fraudulent data would not be emphasized.

By comparing with KNN classifier in project 1, this unbalanced target value distribution may cause biased neighborhood boundry determinination, and thus cause the model more easily to become underfit or overfit. As most of data are non-fraud, so when it comes to prediction, it is more likely that a test point is classified as non-fraud given that it is actually fraud transaction, which is bad performance on identifying minority classes.

To evaluate this model, we can use confusion matrix with identification of tp,fp,tn,fn to classify the predictions and actual data. We can also use precision, recall, F1 score after calculating the confusion matrix as well as ROC curve and AUC to determine the model performance under different parameter or feature selections.

Explain how these graphs could provide meaningful information about anomaly detection using a gaussian model. [0.5]

Given the histogram for each feature categorized by fraud and non-fraud class, we can easily locate the distribution for these two classes in every feature. With data visualizations, we now have a overview of gaussian model parameters such as mean and variance for each feature. We can also find out which feature distribution is convex(only one peak) and non-convex(with multiple peaks). To deal with non-convex distribution, we may implement gaussian mixture models.

It also helps determine which features we should pick to build the gaussian model to ensure the highest performance. For example, if the fraud distribution and non-fraud distribution is not located/centralized in the same interval,it means this feature is helpful to identify the classes and is useful to fit the model. If the distribution of two or more features have extreme overlap so that the peak interval is disrupted and thus affect the anomaly detection. All in all, I think feature v3,v4,v10,v11,v12,v14,v16,v17 distribution is straightforward and should be considered for future model input

Part 2: Single feature model with one Gaussian distribution: [2.5 Marks]¶

We'll start by making a prediction using a single feature of our dataset at a time.

Please note that we only use V features in our model.

a. Fitting regardless of class:

  1. Fit a single Gaussian distribution on a single feature of the full training dataset (both classes) using sklearn.mixture.GaussianMixture when n_components=1.
  2. Compute AUC (Area under the ROC Curve) based on sklearn.mixture.GaussianMixture.score_samples on both the full training set and validation set (including both classes).
  3. Repeat the above steps for each of the features and present your findings in a table.
  4. Find the best 3 features to distinguish fraud transactions from not-fraud transactions based on the AUC of the validation set. [0.2]
  5. Make a prediction based on a model's scores: If the score_samples is lower than a threshold, we consider that transaction as a fraud. Find an optimal threshold that maximizes the F1 Score of the validation set for each of those 3 features separately. (Do not check every possible value for threshold, come up with a faster way!) Compute F1 score using sklearn.metrics.f1_score. [0.5]
  6. Report the complexity of your method (Big O notation) for determining the optimal threshold.[0.5]

b. Fitting based on class:

  1. Pick 3 features that had the best AUC in Part 2a.
  2. Compute AUC and F1 score when you fit a Gaussian only on not-fraud transactions (instead of all the transactions).
  3. Compare your results from parts 2a and 2b (AUC and F1 score) in a table. [0.8]
  4. Are these results different or similar? Why?[0.5]

from sklearn.mixture import GaussianMixture
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve
from sklearn.metrics import auc
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score,f1_score

auc_train_score = []
auc_val_score = []
b = np.arange(28)

for i in b:
  # Traverse all v1-28 features and return gaussian model AUC score for X_train
  data_train = X_train.iloc[:,i].values.reshape(-1, 1)
  gm = GaussianMixture(n_components = 1, covariance_type = 'full', random_state=0)
  gm.fit(data_train)
  c_train = gm.score_samples(data_train)
  auc_train = roc_auc_score(y_train,-1*c_train)
  auc_train_score.append(auc_train)

  # Fit the X_validation dataset into previous training model to get AUC score
  data_val = X_val.iloc[:,i].values.reshape(-1, 1)
  c_val = gm.score_samples(data_val)
  auc_val = roc_auc_score(y_val,-1*c_val)
  auc_val_score.append(auc_val)

# Convert lists to DataFrames
df_train = pd.DataFrame(auc_train_score, columns=['AUC_Train'])
df_val = pd.DataFrame(auc_val_score, columns=['AUC_Validation'])

# Use concat to combine two dataframe into one table
table = pd.concat([df_train, df_val], axis=1)
print(table)

my_list = [13,9,3]

best_thresholds = [] # list to store best threshold for each feature

for i in my_list:
  print(f'Iteration for feature v{i+1}')

  # Use feature V14, V10, V4 to construct GMM model by X_train
  data_train = X_train.iloc[:, i].values.reshape(-1, 1)
  gm = GaussianMixture(n_components=1, covariance_type='full', random_state=0)
  gm.fit(data_train)

  # Use GMM model to get per-sample likelihood (scores) for X_validation
  data_val = X_val.iloc[:, i].values.reshape(-1, 1)
  scores = gm.score_samples(data_val)

  thresholds = np.linspace(min(scores), max(scores), 200) # Generate more threshold value
  f1_scores = []
  for threshold in thresholds:
    f1 = f1_score(y_val, scores < threshold)
    f1_scores.append(f1)

    # Return the best threshold index by locating highest f1_score index
  best_threshold = thresholds[np.argmax(f1_scores)]
  best_thresholds.append(best_threshold)

  print(f'Best F1 score: {max(f1_scores)} at threshold: {best_threshold}')
  print()

print(f'Best thresholds for features are: {best_thresholds}')

Determine model complexity:

In the code to return best threshold, I created a list with 200 entries and use for loop to traverse all the values, the complexity for this part is O(200). The complexity to identify the best threshold is O(200) by traverse all the 200 F1_scores in list.

The total complexity is O(200n+200). After eliminating the constants, the final complexity is O(n).

Part 4: Single feature model with two Gaussian distributions. [2 Marks]¶

Now we will use two different distributions for fraud and not-fraud transactions.

  1. Fit a Gaussian distribution ($G_1$) on a feature of not-fraud transactions using sklearn.mixture.GaussianMixture when n_components=1. [0.25]
  2. Fit another Gaussian distribution ($G_2$) on the same feature but for fraud transactions using sklearn.mixture.GaussianMixture when n_components=1. [0.25]
  3. Compute the score samples ($S$) for both $G_1$ and $G_2$ on the validation set to get $S_1$ and $S_2$, respectively. [0.25]
  4. Find an optimal $c$ (a real number) that maximizes validation set F1 Score for a model such that if $S_1 < c \times S_2$, the transaction is classified as an anomaly. For example, if $c=1$ we could say that if $S_2$ is greater than $S_1$, ($S_1$<$S_2$) then the transaction is an anomaly (the transaction belongs to the $G_2$ distribution which represents fraud transactions). For start consider $c$ in $[0,10]$ with steps of 0.1, you can change this window in your experiments if needed. [0.25]
  5. Repeat the steps above for all the features. What is the best F1 Score that you get for training and validation? Which feature and what c? [1]

Part 5: Multivariate and Mixture of Gaussians Distribution [4 Marks]¶

We now want to build an outlier detection model that performs well in terms of F1 score. To design your model, you can benefit from:

  • No restrictions on the number of features - use as few or as many as you want! (multivariate).
  • To fit your model, you can take advantage of the Gaussian mixture model, where you can set the number of components help.
  • You can choose to fit your Gaussians on not-fraud transactions or to both classes.

It is up to you how to design your model. Try at least 10 different models and report the AUC for both training and validation sets (if applicable) and the best F1 score for both training and validation sets for each model. What kind of model works better? How many features are best (and which ones)? How many Gaussians? How many components? Summarize your findings with tables or plots. [4]

HINT !

You might want to try a two-gaussian model, multiple features, a single component for the valid transaction, and multiple components for fraud ones! Why does it make sense to have multiple components for fraud transactions?

Introduction of self-designed model: To find better combinations achieve higher performance, I plan to use model 1 - model 7 using one Gaussian by changing different feture and components to find which features and components are the best using iterations. In moodel 8 - model 10, I plan to use the features and components selected from previous models to build multiple gaussian model to maximize its performance.

from sklearn.mixture import GaussianMixture

# Extract feature v17 from both train and validation set, and fit GMM model
v17_train = X_train['V17'].values.reshape(-1,1)
v17_val = X_val['V17'].values.reshape(-1,1)
gm_v17 = GaussianMixture(n_components = 2, covariance_type = 'full', random_state=0)
gm_v17.fit(v17_train)
score_v17_train = gm_v17.score_samples(v17_train)
score_v17_val = gm_v17.score_samples(v17_val)
auc_train_v17 = roc_auc_score(y_train,-1*score_v17_train)
auc_val_v17 = roc_auc_score(y_val,-1*score_v17_val)

thresholds_v17 = np.linspace(min(score_v17_val), max(score_v17_val), 100) # Generate more threshold value
f1_scores_train_v17 = []
f1_scores_val_v17 = []

# Traverse the thresholds to find the best F1 score for the training set
for threshold in thresholds_v17:
    f1_train = f1_score(y_train, score_v17_train < threshold)
    f1_scores_train_v17.append(f1_train)

# Find the best F1 score and its corresponding threshold for the training set
best_f1_train_v17 = max(f1_scores_train_v17)
best_threshold_train_v17 = thresholds_v17[np.argmax(f1_scores_train_v17)]

# Traverse the thresholds to find the best F1 score for the validation set
for threshold in thresholds_v17:
    f1_val = f1_score(y_val, score_v17_val < threshold)
    f1_scores_val_v17.append(f1_val)

# Find the best F1 score and its corresponding threshold for the validation set
best_f1_val_v17 = max(f1_scores_val_v17)
best_threshold_val_v17 = thresholds_v17[np.argmax(f1_scores_val_v17)]

print(f"For the feature V17:")
print(f"Training AUC: {auc_train_v17}")
print(f"Validation AUC: {auc_val_v17}")
print(f"Best F1 score for training set: {best_f1_train_v17} at threshold: {best_threshold_train_v17}")
print(f"Best F1 score for validation set: {best_f1_val_v17} at threshold: {best_threshold_val_v17}")

component_v17 = np.arange(1, 14)
auc_train_scores = []
auc_val_scores = []
best_f1_train_scores = []
best_f1_val_scores = []

v17_train = X_train['V17'].values.reshape(-1, 1)
v17_val = X_val['V17'].values.reshape(-1, 1)

for comp in component_v17:
    gm_v17 = GaussianMixture(n_components=comp, covariance_type='full', random_state=0)
    gm_v17.fit(v17_train)

    score_v17_train = gm_v17.score_samples(v17_train)
    score_v17_val = gm_v17.score_samples(v17_val)

    auc_train_v17 = roc_auc_score(y_train, -score_v17_train)
    auc_val_v17 = roc_auc_score(y_val, -score_v17_val)

    thresholds = np.linspace(min(score_v17_train), max(score_v17_train), 100)
    f1_scores = [f1_score(y_train, score_v17_train < threshold) for threshold in thresholds]
    best_f1_train = max(f1_scores)

    thresholds = np.linspace(min(score_v17_val), max(score_v17_val), 100)
    f1_scores = [f1_score(y_val, score_v17_val < threshold) for threshold in thresholds]
    best_f1_val = max(f1_scores)

    auc_train_scores.append(auc_train_v17)
    auc_val_scores.append(auc_val_v17)
    best_f1_train_scores.append(best_f1_train)
    best_f1_val_scores.append(best_f1_val)

results = pd.DataFrame({

    'AUC_Val': auc_val_scores,

})

    score_model9_nf_val = gm9_nf.score_samples(v_model9_val)

    for f in f_comp_model9:

            f1_scores_model9.append(f1)

        max_f1 = max(f1_scores_model9)
        best_c_current = C[np.argmax(f1_scores_model9)]
        results.append((nf, f, best_c_current, max_f1))
        print(f'NF Components: {nf}, F Components: {f} - Threshold: {best_c_current} Best F1 score: {max_f1}')

nf_comp_model10 = np.arange(2,10)
f_comp_model10 = np.arange(4,10)

# Using non-fraud data
v17_train_nf = X_train['V17'][y_train==0].values.reshape(-1, 1)
v14_train_nf = X_train['V14'][y_train==0].values.reshape(-1, 1)
v12_train_nf = X_train['V12'][y_train==0].values.reshape(-1, 1)
v_model10_nf_train = np.hstack((v17_train_nf,v14_train_nf,v12_train_nf))

v17_val = X_val['V17'].values.reshape(-1, 1)
v14_val = X_val['V14'].values.reshape(-1, 1)
v12_val = X_val['V12'].values.reshape(-1, 1)
v_model10_val = np.hstack((v17_val, v14_val, v12_val))

# Using fraud data
v17_train_f = X_train['V17'][y_train==1].values.reshape(-1, 1)
v14_train_f = X_train['V14'][y_train==1].values.reshape(-1, 1)
v12_train_f = X_train['V12'][y_train==1].values.reshape(-1, 1)
v_model10_f_train = np.hstack((v17_train_f,v14_train_f,v12_train_f))

results = []

for nf in nf_comp_model10:
    gm10_nf = GaussianMixture(n_components=nf, covariance_type='full', random_state=0)
    gm10_nf.fit(v_model10_nf_train)
    score_model10_nf_val = gm10_nf.score_samples(v_model10_val)

    for f in f_comp_model10:
        gm10_f = GaussianMixture(n_components=f, covariance_type='full', random_state=0)
        gm10_f.fit(v_model10_f_train)
        score_model10_f_val = gm10_f.score_samples(v_model10_val)

        # Compute for F1 score using c value range 0 - 10
        C = np.arange(0, 10.1, 0.1)
        f1_scores_model10 = []

        for c in C:
            predictions = score_model10_nf_val < c * score_model10_f_val
            f1 = f1_score(y_val, predictions)
            f1_scores_model10.append(f1)

        max_f1 = max(f1_scores_model10)
        best_c_current = C[np.argmax(f1_scores_model10)]
        results.append((nf, f, max_f1, best_c_current))
        print(f'NF Components: {nf}, F Components: {f} - Best threshold: {best_c_current} Best F1 score: {max_f1}')

Part 7: Is Gaussian the only useful distribution? [1 Mark]¶

Search for other distributions that could be used to model the data. How popular are they? Is there a specific situation where a distribution works better? How can we find a suitable distribution to model our data? Do not forget to include your references.

As the feature data is continuous and target data is discrete, there are four distributions I believe that fcould also fit the model.

1: T-distribution

From the formula, T-distribution is often used in hypothesis testing and it is a standardized distribution. This distribution is more sensitive to anomaly points at the tail part. However, it would be similar to normal distribution for a large sample size data modelling. It could be applied to partial testing in the modelling process.

2: Exponential distribution

Exponential distribution provides a probability density function which is distributed exponential, which means there is an exist interval that majority of data is located within the interval. The distribution is characterized by a rate parameter lambda, which is the average number of events in an interval. Higher lambda means the event happens more frequently. It might help predict the expect time or transactions when the next fraud transasction occurs.

3: Possion distribution Although the data is continuous, possion distribution can help identify the probability of fraud/non-fraud transaction occured during a time interval. However, we'd ensure that the fitted data to be integer values and the distribution plot is not as smooth as normal distribution. To solve it, we need to use the features that are deleted(time and amount) to build a possion distribution model.

4: Binomial distribution This distribuition refers to the probability of success or failure within a number of trials. Among 1000 transactions, the probability of fraud/non-fraud transactions occur is important to build a forecasting model. Meantime, we need to be careful that the feature data can be fitted into this discrete distribution.
